04102nam a22006495i 9781442688599DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426885997 a10.3138/97814426885992doi  a(DE-B1597)626580  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB995.L654bB73 2007eb 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1911 aBraman, Brian J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMeaning and Authenticity :bBernard Lonergan and Charles Taylor on the Drama of Authentic Human Existence /cBrian J. Braman. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (160 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Martin Heidegger: The One Thing Needful -- t2 Charles Taylor: Ethics and the Expressivist Turn -- t3 Bernard Lonergan: On Being Oneself -- t4 Taylor and Lonergan: Dialogue and Dialectic -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe language of self-fulfilment, self-realization, and self-actualization (in short, ‘authenticity’) has become common in contemporary culture. The desire to be authentic is implicitly a desire to shape one’s self in accordance with an ideal, and the concern for what it means to be authentic is, in many ways, the modern form of the ancient question what is the life of excellence? However, this notion of authenticity has its critics: Christopher Lasch, for instance, who equates it with a form of narcissism and Theodor Adorno, who views it as a glorification of privatism.Brian J. Braman argues that, despite such criticisms, it is possible to speak about human authenticity as something that addresses contemporary concerns as well as the ancient preoccupation with the nature of the good life. He refers to the work of Bernard Lonergan and Charles Taylor, thinkers who place a high value on the search for human authenticity. Lonergan discusses authenticity in terms of a three-fold conversion–intellectual, moral, and religious–while Taylor views authenticity as a rich, vibrant, and important addition to conversations about what it means to be human.Meaning and Authenticity is an engaging dialogue between these two thinkers, both of whom maintain that there is a normative conception of authentic human life that overcomes moral relativism, narcissism, privatism, and the collapse of the public self.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAuthenticity (Philosophy). 0aConduct of life. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268859940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442688599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442688599/original  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK